      <article class="prose" id="prose-content">

        <p>Noel had grown used to competition, but Reeene was different from anyone he had faced before.

          She was his rival—but an unpredictable one.

          Reene never stayed consistent. On some days, she would confidently declare herself better than Noel, analyzing
          his work
          and pointing out every flaw she could imagine. On other days, she would completely reverse her position,
          saying she
          wasn’t even interested in competition and that people were overthinking the rivalry.

        </p>
        <p>It left everyone around her confused.

          Even Noel couldn’t fully read her.

          At one point, Reene would praise his latest project, saying it was impressive and “almost untouchable.” The
          next moment,
          she would question how it even made it to the top, as if she had forgotten her earlier words.
        </p>

        <p>Noel stopped trying to predict her behavior.

          Instead, he focused on his own path.

          While Reene jumped between ideas, starting projects and abandoning them halfway, Noel kept building steadily.
          His
          consistency became his advantage. Every new release showed growth, while Reene’s shifting attention made her
          progress
          hard to measure.
        </p>
        <p><br></p>

        <p>Their rivalry became something people talked about online. Some fans argued that Reene had potential to
          surpass Noel if
          she ever stayed focused. Others believed Noel had already pulled too far ahead.
        </p>

        <p>Reene, hearing all of this, would sometimes laugh it off and say she didn’t care. Other times, she would take
          it
          personally and promise she would prove everyone wrong. But those promises often faded as quickly as they came.
          .</p>

        <div class="scene-break">✦ ✦ ✦</div>

        <p>Noel noticed something over time: Reene wasn’t truly lacking talent—she was just caught in her own
          uncertainty. She
          couldn’t decide whether she wanted to compete, improve, or step away entirely.

          And that indecision shaped everything she did.

        </p>

        <p>Noel, on the other hand, had already chosen his direction.

          So while Reene kept shifting between versions of herself, Noel simply kept moving forward—quietly, steadily,
          and without
          distraction.

          And in the end, that difference mattered more than anything they said about each other</p>

      </article>

